        Official Singles Chart on 15/10/2021

        15 October 2021 - 21 October 2021

        The Official Singles Chart Top 100 reflects the UK’s biggest songs of the week, based on audio and video streams, downloads, CDs and vinyl, compiled by the Official Charts Company. The UK Top 40 is broadcast on BBC Radio 1. View the biggest songs of 2025.

        Easy On Me - Adele doing Adele, doing what Adele does. If you like what's come before, you'll love it. If you want a little variety, then perhaps the album might have it.         Dave Knight

        Just proves how streaming is to blame for making a very stagnant top 100.
        There are quite a few singles which have been inside the top 100 for at least a year.
        This prevents new material to come along.
        This would never have happened in a physical format age because typically once someone's bought the single it peaks within a few weeks and drops away a few weeks later meaning new singles came into the chart keeping it fresh and active.
        But because fans now use Spotify for example as their player it causes songs to stay in the charts for many months sometimes over a year, and in one or two cases 2 years.
        This is very very sad to me.
        Just browse the charts and see how many weeks each single has been over 52 weeks and you will be shocked, or I was anyway.

        D

        WEEKLY CHART REVIEW (15/10/2021 – 21/10/2021)

        🔴 (Negative)

        1) ‘Boyz’ inevitably ends up as the new entry of the week, inside the Top 3! Man, I really like Jesy Nelson in general as a singer, but this kind of song just doesn’t work for her, at all. The thing is, I’m not all surprised that she decided to go solo, since she recently revealed in interviews how out of place she felt compared to the other Little Mix girls despite all the support that they gave her, but I’ve always thought of her as the member who always brought the most swagger & sass to the group’s singles! Here, for a song that’s meant to be attracting a rebellious guy, her vocals sound incredibly thin & weak in the verses, while the hook feels way too overcompressed & monotonic for it to sound anywhere close to flirty or enticing. The verse from Nicki sounds so phoned in too, to the point where I don’t remember any of it literally by the end of the song hardly a minute later! Again, Jesy absolutely doesn’t deserve all the hate she’s been getting on social media about her appearance or straying away from Jade, Leigh-Anne & Perrie, but for as much as I respect her as a person for having to put with all of that abuse for years, if she keeps releasing songs as dated & derivative as this, then the hype isn’t going to last! We saw it happen with ZAYN a few years ago, I really don’t want to see the same thing with Jesy. :/

        2) Radio 1 continue to choose the same songs to play & they really disappointed me again! Seriously, the first one makes me sad for personal reasons (‘I Guess I’m In Love’) & the two that followed give me a splitting headache (‘Bad Day’ & ‘Life Goes On’).

        3) ‘Wid It’ drops out of the Top 40 this week! I don’t get why this soured on so many people so fast, but ‘Wasted’ has completely stabilised.

        🟠 (Mixed)

        1) Arz gained a few places with ‘Alone With You’! It’s growing on me slightly, but whenever I hear this, I’m always reminded of how underrated ‘Hostage’ (the Billie Eilish song that it samples) is.

        2) ‘Clash’ is the biggest ACR victim this week! Two of my favourite British rappers feature on this, but it still had a very good run, so I’m not too disheartened about it leaving.

        🟢 (Positive)

        1) I already wrote a completely separate post about this, but ‘Cold Heart’ as the new #1 single is so good to see that it has to be mentioned twice! It’s really satisfying seeing an older artist still being able to top this chart in an era dominated by streaming & while I’ll always be disappointed inside that Dua Lipa never got here with a song from ‘Future Nostalgia’, this at least mostly makes up for it.

        2) Relating to the above point, Ed Sheeran’s 15 consecutive weeks at #1 are finally over! Again, I don’t even mind either of the songs he’s recently been at the top with, but seeing the same artist at the top of the charts for this long was always going to get boring, no matter who it is.

        3) ‘Love Tonight’ enters the Top 20! This definitely stands out in terms of EDM hits that we’ve had in 2021, whether it’s the original or any of the remixes by some of those, massive DJs, e.g. David Guetta, Robin Schulz, etc.

        4) ‘Meet Me At Our Spot’ also entered the Top 20 this week, continuing an incredibly successful year for rock or at the very least rock-influenced music! Willow’s & Tyler Cole’s vocals are an amazing fir for one another, so it’s awesome that Radio 1 are all over this right now.

        5) Despite being narrowly denied a place in the region last week, ‘Tell Me Something Good’ has finally broken into the Top 40! The soulful vocals from Chaka Khan’s original version were always going to be a massive selling point for me, but I particularly love how it’s juxtaposed over the bubbling, rolling bass. I’m not sure how I feel about the sharp stabs of the rave synths in places, but they’re yet another feature of the production that really ramps up the energy behind this without taking away much of the funkiness from the song of the same name from 37 years ago! Older listeners or those who aren’t into EDM very much might not feel that this take on it does the original 1974 hit any justice, but to everyone else, it’s a lot of fun & I’d highly recommend it.

        6) ‘Seventeen Going Under’ goes Top 40 thanks to the album boost! Honestly, Sam Fender sounds absolutely incredible here & the instrumentation that he’s belting over makes his voice even more impressive. Glad that he finally makes the region for the first time in his career!

        7) Speaking of which, the parent album for the same name easily debuts at #1 on the albums chart! I actually haven’t ‘Seventeen Going Under’ in full yet, but I’ve either liked or loved every track from it that’s been getting at least some airplay, so that has to be a promising sign, right?

        8) I’ll save my full commentary on this until next week, but man, the nearly six years we’ve been waiting for Adele to release new music was definitely worth it! I don’t think ‘Easy On Me’ is her strongest of lead singles by any means & I think it would’ve worked better as an album closer (which is very unlikely for the first song to be officially released from it), but it still has all the classic features of an Adele ballad that we all know & love, so I’m really glad that we’re continuing to hear that side of her in this. Probably a light 9/10 & that’s not even after 24 hours yet, so expect that score to go up before next Friday!

        My latest personal chart (replace the * with an “o”): www.crownnote.c*m/charts/piran/pirans-top-50-11
